body:

**System used:**
Windows 10
(Not a GPU/CUDA specific issue)

**Issue faced:**
cuda_provider_factory.h has an include #include "core/framework/provider_options.h", while all header files are placed in a single folder after installation. 

**Fix:**
For me, changing #include "core/framework/provider_options.h" to #include "provider_options.h" worked. 

Shouldn't this be taken care of by Visual studio/onnxruntime nuget package itself?

title: Fix to_dlpack Failure on PyTorch-1.10
body:
Current DLPack doesn't support bool type and PyTorch disables converting bool tensor to DLPack in recent commit. This PR is to add fix for this case so ORTModule can run using bool tensor with recent nightly PyTorch.

PyTorch also updated the DLPack version, so this PR also updates the DLPack submodule in ORT.

title: How to optimize 32 bit memory/cpu usage in c++

labels.name: core runtime
labels.description: issues related to core runtime

body:
**Describe the performance question**
Part of the memory usage is from the model, but there is an additional ~160 MB usage we'd like to reduce as much as possible. Is there any way to lower this memory either changing some compilation or configuration option(s) in OnnxRuntime? 

Also, having several evaluating threads seems to consume as follows: 160 MB one thread, 310 MB with two threads and up to 610MB with 4 threads. We have several evaluating threads that share the session in this configuration but it seems that each additional thread requires a constant amount of memory that adds up to the total process. Is there a way to reduce this amount per thread? In this setup, evaluating threads run the session continuously (one after another) and we can notice that the more threads we have, the evaluation time takes also longer. The profiling output shows that costly operations take more kernel time than the same operations with fewer threads, is there a way to improve this, apart from using intrathreads (that seem to help more than inter threads)? 

I tried to use the ort model instead of the onnx model too, first exporting the model and with the following code:

```
Ort::SessionOptions session_options;
...

session_options.AddConfigEntry("session.load_model_format", "ORT");
```
But no significant change was found in memory/cpu usage. 

**Urgency**
Decision to include onnxruntime will be taken next week depending on memory/cpu usage.

**System information**
- OS Platform: Windows PC
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): Binary, downloaded from https://www.nuget.org/packages/Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime/
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.8.1
- CPU mode, c++ program compiled in 32bit 

**Labels**
type: performance, type:support

title: Resnet - converted Onnx model is 2.9X slower than pyTorch model in V100 gpu

labels.name: ep:CUDA
labels.description: issues related to the CUDA execution provider

body:
**Describe the bug**
Hi ort team,

We are using ORT to serve our models. 
Our original models are torch models. We will first convert torch models to ONNX models using torch.onnx.export(opset_version=x) and run inference with the converted ONNX models. We do it for speed, usually, ONNX model can be 1.3x~2x faster than original pyTorch model.

However, recently, we met a resnet model. To our surprise, after converted to onnx model, its speed is 2.9x slower than original pyTorch model.  We would like to ask your help to figure out why and how to resolve it. Thanks.

Below is the test result:
- The number of input samples is 15k

| Framework | Inference Time (s) | Throughput(samples/s/gpu) |
| ------------- | ------------- | ------------- |
| PyTorch | 248.95 | **60.25** |
| Onnx+Opset12 | 721.74 | **20.78** |
| Onnx+Opset13 | 725.58 | **20.67**  |

Note:
1. All the tests are based on the same settings, both models are using fp32, with the same batch_size=32. 
2. We tested several torch versions (1.9.1, 1.8.0), onnxruntime versions (1.8.1, 1.6.0), Onnx opset version (opset12 and opset13) and GPU types (V100 and A100), they had the same behaviors. To keep this ticket clear and easy to reproduce, the numbers I reported in the table were run in ORT1.8.1, torch1.9.1+cu111 in V100, all packages are the latest versions. But even test on other torch versions, onnxruntime versions or GPU types, this issue is consistent. 

**Urgency**
We are running an ONNX inference platform for Microsoft ads users. This is a blocking issue for users running such kinds of models.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Ubuntu 18.04.2 LTS
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): binary
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.8.1, install command: pip install onnxruntime-gpu==1.8.1
- Torch version: 1.9.1+cu111, install command: pip3 install torch==1.9.1+cu111 torchvision==0.10.1+cu111 torchaudio==0.9.1 -f https://download.pytorch.org/whl/torch_stable.html
- Python version: 3.6.8
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): N/A
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): N/A
- CUDA/cuDNN version: Driver Version: 455.45.01    CUDA Version: 11.1 
- GPU model and memory: V100, 16GB
 We also tested it in (A100, 40GB.  AML SKU: Standard_ND96asr_v4 ) with batch_size=32 and 128. The results are consistent. 

**To Reproduce**
- Describe steps/code to reproduce the behavior.

Below is the core code snippet that I used to covert torch model to onnx model and test their inference time. Detailed code, model and data are attached below.
* convert_torch_to_onnx(): convert torch model to onnx model
* torch_evaluate(): torch inference
* onnx_evaluate(): onnx inference

```python
def load_torch_model(args):
    model_name="BiT-M-R152x2"
    model = models.KNOWN_MODELS[model_name](head_size=3, zero_head=True)
    model = torch.nn.DataParallel(model)
    try:
        checkpoint = torch.load(args.torch_model_path, map_location="cpu")
        print(f"Found saved model to resume from at '{args.torch_model_path}'")
        step = checkpoint["step"]
        model.load_state_dict(checkpoint["model"])
        print(f"Resumed at step {step}", )
    except FileNotFoundError:
        print("Fine-tuning from BiT", flush=True)
    model.to(args.device)
    model.eval()
    return model

def convert_torch_to_onnx(args):
    torch_model = load_torch_model(args)
    batch_size = 1 # batch_size is only used to generate the random input data.
    image_size = 480 # max_seq_len is corresponding to training, in our example roberta model, the max_seq_len is 32
    input_image       = torch.FloatTensor(torch.zeros((batch_size, 3, image_size, image_size), dtype=torch.float))
    input_image = input_image.cuda()
    input_tensors =  (input_image, )
    input_names = ["input_image"]
    output_names = ["logits"]
    dynamic_axes={'input_image':{0:'batch_size'}, 'logits':{0:'batch_size'}}
    print("model export begins ... ")
    torch.onnx.export(
        torch_model.module,     # model being run
        input_tensors,          # model input (or a tuple for multiple inputs)
        args.output_onnx_model_path,   # where to save the model (can be a file or file-like object)
        export_params=True,        # store the trained parameter weights inside the model file
        opset_version=args.opset_version,          # the ONNX version to export the model to
        do_constant_folding=True,  # whether to execute constant folding for optimization
        verbose=True,              # verbose=True causes the exporter to print out a human-readable representation of the network
        input_names = input_names,   # the model's input names
        output_names = output_names, # the model's output names
        dynamic_axes= dynamic_axes,  # variable lenght axes
        use_external_data_format=False # should be true for model size >2GB
    )
    print("model export done.")

def torch_evaluate(args):
    torch_model = load_torch_model(args)
    val_loader = get_val_loader(args)

    accumulated_inference_time = 0
    with torch.no_grad():
        for i, (id, data, target) in enumerate(val_loader):
            data = data.to(args.device)
            #below is pytorch inference code
            start_stamp = time.time()
            #pred = torch_model(data)
            with torch.cuda.amp.autocast():
                pred = torch_model(data)
            torch.cuda.synchronize()
            accumulated_inference_time += time.time() - start_stamp

    print(f"Total Pytorch model inference time is {accumulated_inference_time}")

def onnx_evaluate(args):
    val_loader = get_val_loader(args)
    import onnxruntime as ort
    sess_options = ort.SessionOptions()
    sess_options.graph_optimization_level = ort.GraphOptimizationLevel.ORT_ENABLE_ALL
    sess_options.intra_op_num_threads = 0
    sess = ort.InferenceSession(args.onnx_model_path, sess_options)
    input_name = sess.get_inputs()[0].name
    label_name = sess.get_outputs()[0].name
    def to_numpy(torch_tensor):
        return torch_tensor.detach().cpu().numpy() if torch_tensor.requires_grad else torch_tensor.cpu().numpy()

    accumulated_inference_time = 0
    with torch.no_grad():
        for i, (id, data, target) in enumerate(val_loader):
            data = data.to(args.device)
            #below is onnx inference code
            start_stamp = time.time()
            pred = sess.run([label_name], {input_name: to_numpy(data)})[0]
            accumulated_inference_time += time.time() - start_stamp

    print(f"Total Onnx model inference time is {accumulated_inference_time}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    script_start_time = time.time()
    parser = argparse.ArgumentParser()
    parser.add_argument("--mode", type=str, help='torchInference, onnxInference, or torch2Onnx')

    args, unknown = parser.parse_known_args()

    args.batch_size = 32
    args.image_size = 480
    args.device = torch.device("cuda" if torch.cuda.is_available() else "cpu")
    args.n_gpu = torch.cuda.device_count()
    print(" ARGS.device " + str(args.device) + "  ARGS.n_gpu " + str(args.n_gpu))

    args.test_file_path = "./data/input.tsv"
    if args.mode == "torchInference":
        args.torch_model_path = "./model/bit.pth.tar"
        args.outputfilename = './output/torch_result.tsv'
        torch_evaluate(args)
    elif args.mode == "onnxInference":
        args.onnx_model_path = "./model/graph_opset12.onnx"
        args.outputfilename = './output/onnx_opset12_result.tsv'
        onnx_evaluate(args)
    elif args.mode == "torch2Onnx":
        args.torch_model_path = "./model/bit.pth.tar"
        args.output_onnx_model_path = "./model/graph_opset13.onnx"
        args.opset_version = 13
        convert_torch_to_onnx(args)
    else:
        raise Exception("Unrecognized --mode, please use torchInference, onnxInference, or torch2Onnx")
```

- Attach the ONNX model to the issue (where applicable) to expedite investigation.
https://drive.google.com/file/d/1EVqAsYAaju9vU5AdOlmAYXRWAvcZHIG3/view?usp=sharing

It contains 6 files:
1. resnetInference_torch_vs_onnx.py: test code
2. models.py: model definition code
3. ./data/input.tsv: input data
4. ./model/bit.pth.tar: original torch model
5. ./model/graph_opset12.onnx: converted onnx opset12
6. ./model/graph_opset13.onnx: converted onnx opset13

Commands:
1. To get the inference time of Torch model: ```python resnetInference_torch_vs_onnx.py --mode torchInference```
2. To get the inference time of Onnx model: ```python resnetInference_torch_vs_onnx.py --mode onnxInference```
3. To convert Torch model to onnx model: ```python resnetInference_torch_vs_onnx.py --mode torch2Onnx```

**Expected behavior**
I expect the inference speed of the converted onnx model should be faster than the original torch model, at least not slower than torch model.

title: [js/web] Inference failing on larger inputs
body:
**Describe the bug**
Model inference is breaking when dynamic axes (height and width) are "too large". When a tensor of size  `[1, 3, 512, 512]` is fed in, an exception is thrown with some seemingly random error code (i.e. `9636832`). This may not be the exact breaking point, but it certainly breaks here. When a smaller tensor is fed in (i.e. `[1, 3, 128, 128]`), inference works just fine.

For the 512x512 input the evolution of intermediate sizes is as follows:

1. `[1, 3, 512, 512]` (Input)
2. `[1, 3, 1024, 1024]` (Resize)
3. `[1, 64, 1024, 1024]` (Conv)
4. `[1, 64, 2048, 2048]` (Resize)
5. `[1, 64, 2048, 2048]` (Conv)
6. `[1, 3, 2048, 2048]` (Conv)

I've looked through the code and can see that number of elements in a tensor must be < `2^32-1`, though none of those intermediate sizes get near that. Is there another limitation somewhere I'm not aware of?

Happy to post any code needed.

**Urgency**
Not super urgent, but it would be great if our model could support inputs of this size and greater.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution: Pop!_OS 21.04:
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): binary (NPM)
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.9.0
- Python version: 3.8
- CUDA/cuDNN version: 11.3/8.2.2

Model file: [model.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/7219033/model.zip)

For an input of size `[1, 3, H, W]` output should be `[1, 3, 4*H, 4*W]`.

title: UWP Apps are broken in 1.9 due to Store compliant builds referencing LoadPackagedLibrary
body:
UWP Apps are broken in 1.9 due to Store compliant builds referencing LoadPackagedLibrary

Issue: This change (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/8753) forced the Microsoft.AI.MachineLearning WinRT Store builds to use LoadPackagedLibrary for StoreApps to make the binaries compliant with Store WACK Policies (this is now not needed). Because of this change all load library calls from inside the binaries were swapped to use LoadPackagedLibrary. However, LoadPackagedLibrary cannot find system32 dlls like combase, and other winrt types, and fails.

Fix: For UWP Store binaries use the statically linked desktop binaries. The desktop binaries are now compliant with Store WACK policies, as WACK certification from the latest Windows SDKs do not require Store only apis.

**Description**: FP16_Optimizer wrapper.

## How to Use: ##

Usage:
```
        1. DeepSpeed ZeRO Optimizer Override：
            from onnxruntime.training.optim.fp16_optimizer import FP16_Optimizer
            optimizer = Adam(param_groups,
                             lr=args.lr,
                             weight_decay=args.weight_decay,
                             betas=(args.adam_beta1, args.adam_beta2),
                             eps=args.adam_eps)
            model, optimizer, _, lr_scheduler = deepspeed.initialize(
                model=model,
                optimizer=optimizer,
                args=args,
                lr_scheduler=lr_scheduler,
                mpu=mpu,
                dist_init_required=False)
            if args.fp16:
                optimizer = FP16_Optimizer(optimizer)

        2. Megatron-LM-v1.1.5 Optimizer Override:
            from onnxruntime.training.optim.fp16_optimizer import FP16_Optimizer as ORT_FP16_Optimizer
            optimizer = Adam(param_groups,
                             lr=args.lr,
                             weight_decay=args.weight_decay,
                             betas=(args.adam_beta1, args.adam_beta2),
                             eps=args.adam_eps)
            # Wrap into fp16 optimizer.
            if args.fp16:
                optimizer = FP16_Optimizer(optimizer,
                                           static_loss_scale=args.loss_scale,
                                           dynamic_loss_scale=args.dynamic_loss_scale,
                                           dynamic_loss_args={
                                                'scale_window': args.loss_scale_window,
                                                'min_scale': args.min_scale,

title: Decouple GraphExecutionManager and accept extra exporter options
body:
Current ORTModule class has a TorchModuleInterface which was meant to wrap PyTorch API's only. However, TorchModuleInterface also defines and store GraphExecutionManager, which is responsible for executing ONNX graphs using ORT.

This PR moves GraphExecutionManager from within TorchModuleInterface to ORTModule, which is the main class and responsible for orchestrating the graph. It also allows extra exporter arguments to be specified using internal APIs.

The main benefit of such change is easier ORTModule extensions, as the new version has a lower coupling and higher cohesion.

title: Support external torch cpp extensions on ORTModule
body:
Currently ORTModule is packed with 3 torch c++ extensions and it doesn't support additional extensions without code change.
However, torch c++ extensions are an important means to allow users to add C++ code into ORTModule

This PR introduces an experimental/internal support for custom Torch C++ extensions. Users need to copy their torch c++ extensions into <ortmodule>/torch_cpp_extensions/{cpu,cuda} folder and run `python -m torch_ort.configure` to install it

A future PR can make the copy to ortmodule package optional

title: fix CodeQL warning 'Remote property injection'
body: **Description**: This issue is actually fixed in #9105 but it failed to pass the CodeQL scan. The issue is described in https://codeql.github.com/codeql-query-help/javascript/js-remote-property-injection/. It does not allow to use array indexer with passed-in variables from message even if I performed check before using it. So I have to use a Map to replace the Array. The performance drop should be very trivial.

title: Port ARM64x support
body:
Move ARM64x inbox code that has been in WindowsAI for a while to onnxruntime.

This is inbox specific code that duplicates the WinML DLL into Windows_AI_MachineLearning_x64/Windows_AI_MachineLearning_arm64. This is a request from the team working on ARM64x. They need the x64 DLL with the different name to exist side by side with the ARM64 DLL, but they can't just copy the x64 DLL to a different name, and are requesting teams to link the DLL again with the new name.

(The number 1 reason copying the DLL doesn't work is because the DLL name is also stored in the PE header and used to match to a pdb for debugging, so the renamed DLL would be related to wrong symbols. I think there's other quirks that prevent them from just renaming the DLL and updating the header)

title: Remove usage of wstring_convert
body: **Description**: One customer recently reported that wstring_convert crashes on Windows in VTL1 mode because it calls APIs unavailable there. Also, we removed all uses of wstring_convert from WinML and ORT in the past because, due to what seems like poor implementation on the Microsoft STL, referencing wstring_convert in Windows adds 400KB of conversion code to the binary, including some locale and currency conversion code (even in Release mode with LTO), adding a lot of code that never gets called. In Windows we try to call the Windows API rather than go through the STL.
